    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_171781156" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/171781156" />
    <a title="Kirstine" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5172557-kirstine"><img alt="Kirstine" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1505503603p2/5172557.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/171781156?book_show_action=true">May 28, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kirstine" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kirstine" href="/user/show/5172557-kirstine">Kirstine</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5172557-kirstine?shelf=biography-memoir-real-life">biography-memoir-real-life</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5172557-kirstine?shelf=own">own</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5172557-kirstine?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer171781156" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15503683606516987664">I read it in an afternoon and it is, in one word, <em>beautiful</em>. <br/><br/>This book was, for me, about the simple things we often overlook, mostly because we&apos;re too busy and don&apos;t take the time to actually look, but also because seeing takes a particular state of mind, it requires an openness, that is not always easy to come by. <br/><br/>Jean-Dominique definitely had the time to observe the world, and the immensity of the strength, courage and determination it took to put a fraction of those things onto paper is enou</span>
  <span id="freeText15503683606516987664" style="display:none">I read it in an afternoon and it is, in one word, <em>beautiful</em>. <br /><br />This book was, for me, about the simple things we often overlook, mostly because we're too busy and don't take the time to actually look, but also because seeing takes a particular state of mind, it requires an openness, that is not always easy to come by. <br /><br />Jean-Dominique definitely had the time to observe the world, and the immensity of the strength, courage and determination it took to put a fraction of those things onto paper is enough to make this a worthwhile read. The book might seem pointless at times, but if you remember the state of Jean-Dominique you can appreciate why he might have chosen to write about those exact things. He wanted to say this, not so much for you to read it, but as a way to deal with his loss, a loss that confided him to a bed, paralyzed, while his mind still worked as well as ever. <br /><br />What he gives us is not a story, it is instead a string of thoughts, split into short chapters on various subjects. They’re sometimes rambling, sometimes profound, and always thoughts he couldn't get out any other way. They say actions speak louder than words, but sometimes all you have are words and if you use them right, they'll count for just as much.<br /><br />I can't help but think of this book as his goodbye and hello to the world. I don't think he wrote it for me, the reader, or anyone else, I believe he wrote it mostly for himself. For some reason that's what I like about it. That it isn't for the readers, yet we can still take part in it. I can see the world from his eyes, I can lie in that hospital bed and feel the heavy absence of feeling, living limbs. <br /><br />As he also states in the book, the only other person with this illness/condition in the history of literature is to be found in The Count of Monte Cristo. Regardless of anything else I could say, this is a unique book just because it's such a rare point of view. Don't miss it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15503683606516987664" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

